    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-10-31T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-10-31T02:00:00-05:00" n="624"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d624">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.24/1146: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Second Secretary of Embassy in the Soviet Union</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thompson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-10-31T10:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 31, 1942—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 2—2:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>424. From Faymonville for Stettinius.</p>
                <p>1. Refer to <hi rend="italic">Time</hi> magazine for October 19, quoting Admiral
                    Standley on Lend-Lease aid to the Soviet Union.<note n="54" xml:id="d624fn54"
                        >During this interview with the correspondents, held just before his return
                        to Washington for consultations, among other comments Ambassador Standley
                        was reported to have made “the astounding admission that he did not know
                        what commitments the U. S. had made to Russia, or to what degree they had
                        been met. He said he believed that Brig. Gen. Philip R. Faymonville, head of
                        the U. S. Supply Mission in Moscow, had such information.” (<hi
                            rend="italic">Time</hi>, October 19, 1942, p. 32.)</note> Mr. Thompson
                    who was present at the press interview on which the <hi rend="italic">Time</hi>
                    article was based informs me that it does not accurately reflect the sense of
                    the Ambassador’s remarks but for your information please note that my knowledge
                    of contents of Second Protocol came from draft copy loaned to me by Admiral
                    Standley. My knowledge of general shipments comes from cargo lists shown to me
                    by the Ambassador’s Naval Attaché<note n="55" xml:id="d624fn55">Capt., later
                        Rear Adm., Jack Harlan Duncan, Naval Attaché in the Soviet Union.</note> who
                    receives lists, by agreement, from Chief of British Military Mission. My
                    knowledge of special shipments comes from your cables which in all cases pass
                    through State Department hands, and when Admiral Standley is in Moscow, cables
                    reach him before they reach me. When the Ambassador is in Kuibyshev inbound
                    cables and my answers thereto are repeated to him. Even when the Ambassador is
                    absent my Lend-Lease cables inbound and outbound are repeated to <pb facs="0747"
                        n="741" xml:id="pg_741"/> Kuibyshev so that he may have a complete file upon
                    his return. Please assure Harry Hopkins that his instructions to me to cooperate
                    with other Government officials, have been fully complied with.
                    [Faymonville.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thompson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
